{{One source|date=December 2011}} '''''Cheopji''''' ([[hangul]]:첩지 ;[[hanja]]:疊紙) is a Korean hair accessory decorating the [[Chignon (hairstyle)|chignon]] of ladies when they wear a ceremonial dress. It is usually made of silver, and a frog-shape is its common form. The use of ''cheopji'' began after Baljaegaeheok(hangul: 발제개혁; hanja: 髮制改革; a reformation that prohibited [[Gache]] hair style, then promoted [[Chignon (hairstyle)|Chignon]] hair style) proclaimed by [[Yeongjo of Joseon]]. It was used routinely at court, but ordinary people were to use this only when they wear a ceremonial dress.<ref name="Cheopji">{{ko}} [http://preview.britannica.co.kr/bol/topic.asp?article_id=b07m2319a Cheopji] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415044717/http://preview.britannica.co.kr/bol/topic.asp?article_id=b07m2319a |date=April 15, 2012 }} Korean Britannica Online</ref> [[File:Korean hair pin-Cheopji-01.jpg|thumb|Korean hair pin-Cheopji-01]]
